1
00:01:32,600 --> 00:01:35,637
Dr Halder, Reichsleiter
Bouhler is waiting.

2
00:01:36,688 --> 00:01:40,604
- You don't know what this is about, do you?
- What?

3
00:01:40,652 --> 00:01:43,275
Uh... The letter I received...

4
00:01:44,782 --> 00:01:48,034
It was marked "Reich Committee For
The Scientific Registration... "

5
00:01:48,079 --> 00:01:50,700
"Of Severe Hereditary
Ailments. " That's correct.

6
00:01:50,748 --> 00:01:54,332
It's just I have no idea what that
could possibly have to do with me.

7
00:01:54,378 --> 00:01:57,250
Are you suggesting
there's been a mistake?

8
00:02:33,888 --> 00:02:35,347
Heil Hitler.

9
00:02:37,476 --> 00:02:38,804
Doctor Halder.

10
00:02:41,398 --> 00:02:44,934
- Have we caught you at a bad time?
- Yes.

11
00:02:44,986 --> 00:02:48,153
No, I did have to shuffle
a few tutorials, but...

12
00:02:49,867 --> 00:02:53,487
Not every day one is summoned
to the Chancellery of the Führer.

13
00:02:53,539 --> 00:02:54,949
Indeed.

14
00:02:54,998 --> 00:02:56,541
Sit.

15
00:03:07,474 --> 00:03:09,800
As Chairman of the Party's
Censorship Committee,

16
00:03:09,852 --> 00:03:14,100
it's my job to keep a vigilant
eye on modern literature

17
00:03:14,149 --> 00:03:18,563
to ensure that it embodies the
proper spirit of National Socialism.

18
00:03:19,990 --> 00:03:27,122
I've asked you here to clarify your views on
a matter of personal concern to the Führer.

19
00:03:28,292 --> 00:03:30,167
Your novel.

20
00:03:35,217 --> 00:03:40,296
It raises controversial questions
on the theme of the right to life.

21
00:03:40,349 --> 00:03:43,684
Some of your conclusions
are quite revolutionary.

22
00:03:44,605 --> 00:03:46,148
Are they?

23
00:03:46,190 --> 00:03:50,937
Well, I take it the views expressed
here are ones that you yourself hold?

24
00:03:50,989 --> 00:03:53,481
It's been some years since I wrote it.

25
00:03:54,910 --> 00:03:56,987
Of course, it's a work of fiction.

26
00:03:57,038 --> 00:04:01,536
- Give it back!
- Give it back. Lotte! It's Eric's homework.

27
00:04:01,586 --> 00:04:04,753
- But I know the answer, it's easy.
- Give it back to him.

28
00:04:07,718 --> 00:04:10,293
You're an angel for cooking again.

29
00:04:10,347 --> 00:04:14,725
Hm. Yes, I know I am.

30
00:04:14,769 --> 00:04:17,392
Are you sure you don't mind?

31
00:04:17,440 --> 00:04:19,064
No

32
00:04:20,819 --> 00:04:23,525
- When I get going I can't seem to stop.
- Shh!

33
00:04:24,658 --> 00:04:27,279
No, it's fine.

34
00:04:27,327 --> 00:04:29,784
- Stop it!
- John!

35
00:04:29,830 --> 00:04:31,989
God! Lotte, come here.

36
00:04:32,042 --> 00:04:33,501
John!

37
00:04:35,087 --> 00:04:37,247
Keep stirring this slowly, all right?

38
00:04:38,300 --> 00:04:39,794
That's my girl.

39
00:04:39,843 --> 00:04:42,929
- Johnnie!
- Coming, Mother!

40
00:04:46,269 --> 00:04:50,101
There's someone at the door!

41
00:04:52,277 --> 00:04:53,652
Theodore.

42
00:04:55,322 --> 00:04:57,814
- Didn't you hear me knocking?
- Yes.

43
00:04:58,660 --> 00:05:01,199
A mathematician! Just
the fellow we need.

44
00:05:01,247 --> 00:05:03,038
Helen, your father's here.

45
00:05:03,082 --> 00:05:04,625
- Oh.
- It's you I wanted to see.

46
00:05:04,668 --> 00:05:07,076
- Hello, Father.
- Now, John... John!

47
00:05:07,129 --> 00:05:08,623
Eric?

48
00:05:08,672 --> 00:05:10,333
Help has arrived.

49
00:05:11,926 --> 00:05:14,798
Now, John, I have told you this before.

50
00:05:14,847 --> 00:05:18,098
- You have to shake yourself
out of this apathy. - Right.

51
00:05:18,143 --> 00:05:20,552
I have just come from the Rector...

52
00:05:20,605 --> 00:05:22,148
What are you making?

53
00:05:22,191 --> 00:05:26,320
- Er... Some kind of vegetable...
- Goulash!

54
00:05:27,405 --> 00:05:28,686
Yes.

55
00:05:29,867 --> 00:05:33,403
There are changes coming at the
university sooner than you think.

56
00:05:33,455 --> 00:05:36,540
Promotion will automatically
go to party members.

57
00:05:36,584 --> 00:05:39,372
If you're not careful,
you'll be out of a job.

58
00:05:39,421 --> 00:05:42,292
John!

59
00:05:42,341 --> 00:05:44,465
Yes, Mother!

60
00:05:44,511 --> 00:05:46,172
Mind the onions.

61
00:05:47,515 --> 00:05:48,760
Coming!

62
00:05:49,934 --> 00:05:52,972
- I'm here.
- Where were you?

63
00:05:53,022 --> 00:05:56,724
- No, don't let them take me, Johnnie!
- It's Theodore.

64
00:05:56,776 --> 00:05:59,066
You remember
- Helen's father.

65
00:05:59,113 --> 00:06:02,400
I was sorry to hear you'd
been back at the sanatorium.

66
00:06:02,451 --> 00:06:04,575
Helen, can you please come up?

67
00:06:05,664 --> 00:06:08,831
- You need to go again?
- I couldn't hold it.

68
00:06:08,876 --> 00:06:10,205
Oh, Mother.

69
00:06:10,253 --> 00:06:11,961
"Dans une langue que nous savons,

70
00:06:12,005 --> 00:06:17,214
"nous avons substitué à I'opacité
des sons la transparence des idées. "

71
00:06:17,929 --> 00:06:23,056
Transparency of ideas,
relativity of perception.

72
00:06:24,146 --> 00:06:26,104
Music and faith.

73
00:06:26,149 --> 00:06:28,723
Memory and guilt.

74
00:06:29,987 --> 00:06:33,024
The most potent memories are
those we recapture involuntarily.

75
00:06:33,074 --> 00:06:34,948
A chance sound...

76
00:06:35,786 --> 00:06:41,292
the tap of a spoon against a plate
as he waits there in the library...

77
00:06:42,378 --> 00:06:46,328
and suddenly happiness
floods through him.

78
00:06:46,383 --> 00:06:50,679
He is transported back in time to a train
stopped in the middle of the countryside.

79
00:06:50,723 --> 00:06:54,970
He is watching the sun light up a
little row of trees in the distance.

80
00:06:55,019 --> 00:06:57,428
Outside, a railway man

81
00:06:57,481 --> 00:07:01,943
is tapping a wheel with his hammer, and
it is an echo of this precise sound...

82
00:07:18,967 --> 00:07:20,343
Lovely.

83
00:07:21,262 --> 00:07:23,670
Better leave it there for today.

84
00:07:23,723 --> 00:07:26,096
Go on, have a look.

85
00:07:26,143 --> 00:07:27,768
Off you go.

86
00:07:30,941 --> 00:07:35,605
Ah, Professor Mandelstam, we really should
do something about this, shouldn't we?

87
00:07:35,656 --> 00:07:38,063
Go to the Rector?

88
00:07:38,117 --> 00:07:42,448
Please, John, I don't
think that's a good idea.

89
00:07:42,498 --> 00:07:44,242
For either of us.

90
00:07:44,292 --> 00:07:47,709
In fact, I'm afraid I must go further.

91
00:07:47,755 --> 00:07:49,499
As Head of Department

92
00:07:49,549 --> 00:07:54,841
it is up to me to ensure that the works
of the proscribed authors are removed.

93
00:07:54,889 --> 00:08:00,976
Not only from the library...
but also from your curriculum.

94
00:08:01,940 --> 00:08:06,402
- Which authors did you have in mind?
- Proust for a start.

95
00:08:07,447 --> 00:08:13,035
- Because he's French?
- John, please, don't be obtuse.

96
00:08:13,079 --> 00:08:15,156
What if I refuse to comply?

97
00:08:17,543 --> 00:08:22,123
Then I would have no
option but to dismiss you.

98
00:08:49,835 --> 00:08:51,461
Shit!

99
00:08:58,805 --> 00:09:00,430
Yes?

100
00:09:00,474 --> 00:09:04,936
Isaw your light was on. I was just coming
out of the library. I need your advice.

101
00:09:04,980 --> 00:09:07,935
I'm Anne, by the way. Anne
Hartman. I come to your lectures.

102
00:09:09,695 --> 00:09:13,990
Yes, I've noticed you...
but you're not on my course.

103
00:09:14,033 --> 00:09:15,907
Probably wondering who I was.

104
00:09:15,952 --> 00:09:17,281
Or maybe you weren't.

105
00:09:17,329 --> 00:09:21,163
History... that's what I'm supposed
to be doing but I don't know why.

106
00:09:21,210 --> 00:09:23,417
I just can't see what it
has to do with anything.

107
00:09:23,463 --> 00:09:27,710
Sitting all day in some stuffy lecture
theatre listening to some boring old...

108
00:09:29,220 --> 00:09:32,007
That's not what I mean. Your lectures
- that's why I'm here.

109
00:09:32,056 --> 00:09:34,264
You make them all come alive.

110
00:09:36,938 --> 00:09:39,062
I heard what you said
to Professor Mandelstam.

111
00:09:39,107 --> 00:09:41,730
I wish more people would stand
up for what they believe in.

112
00:09:41,778 --> 00:09:45,195
- And what do you believe in, Miss Hartman?
- That's just it.

113
00:09:45,241 --> 00:09:48,527
I know what I like, I know what's
good, I feel it passionately.

114
00:09:48,578 --> 00:09:52,079
But when it comes to ideas,
they just don't seem real.

115
00:09:52,668 --> 00:09:56,582
Maybe that's why you're
here. At university, I mean.

116
00:09:56,630 --> 00:10:00,546
- To try and connect that passion.
- Did it work for you?

117
00:10:00,594 --> 00:10:02,504
I hope so.

118
00:10:03,514 --> 00:10:05,721
Yes, I think so.

119
00:10:06,560 --> 00:10:08,768
This is what I believe in.

120
00:10:10,106 --> 00:10:11,815
Books?

121
00:10:15,029 --> 00:10:17,985
Does make me sound
rather fusty, doesn't it?

122
00:10:20,453 --> 00:10:24,868
Perhaps you're right. What do a load
of old books have to do with life?

123
00:10:24,918 --> 00:10:28,868
Who knows? It might be liberating
just to chuck them all out.

124
00:10:28,923 --> 00:10:30,915
Make a fresh start.

125
00:10:30,967 --> 00:10:33,423
And here I am writing another one.

126
00:10:34,513 --> 00:10:36,174
Adding to the pile.

127
00:10:39,144 --> 00:10:42,977
- What's it about? Your novel.
- Oh.

128
00:10:47,572 --> 00:10:50,609
- A man who kills his wife.
- Oh!

129
00:10:50,659 --> 00:10:53,495
Because he loves her,
you understand? Erm...

130
00:10:54,623 --> 00:10:57,458
- She's incurably ill.
- How awful.

131
00:10:58,586 --> 00:11:02,716
Yes, I know, really. Whoever is going
to want to read something so depressing?

132
00:11:02,759 --> 00:11:05,048
How awful about the poor woman, I mean.

133
00:11:05,095 --> 00:11:10,720
Of course people will want to read it,
it sounds so romantic. To kill for love...

134
00:11:16,694 --> 00:11:22,282
<i># I crop by the
Neckar I crop by the Rhine</i>

135
00:11:22,326 --> 00:11:25,031
<i># Now I have a sweetheart</i>

136
00:11:25,079 --> 00:11:27,951
<i># And now I have none</i>

137
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:33,957
<i>- # What use is cropping if none is mine
- I love this song.</i>

138
00:11:34,008 --> 00:11:36,297
The problem is I'm imagining it.

139
00:11:37,470 --> 00:11:39,713
Really?

140
00:11:39,765 --> 00:11:41,889
It's not funny, Maurice.

141
00:11:41,935 --> 00:11:44,094
How long has this been going on?

142
00:11:45,563 --> 00:11:47,058
Don't know.

143
00:11:49,486 --> 00:11:52,690
- A few months.
- Three months, six months?

144
00:11:52,740 --> 00:11:54,365
I don't know.

145
00:11:55,285 --> 00:11:57,159
Could it be the end of January, say?

146
00:11:57,204 --> 00:11:59,328
Thereabouts, I suppose.

147
00:11:59,373 --> 00:12:02,210
Why? Do you think there
is some connection to...

148
00:12:02,252 --> 00:12:05,705
Well, we put the country
in the hands of a lunatic...

149
00:12:05,757 --> 00:12:11,762
Taking refuge in fantasy might be a
rational response to an irrational world.

150
00:12:11,807 --> 00:12:14,298
- Why singing?
- I don't know.

151
00:12:14,351 --> 00:12:17,603
No idea?

152
00:12:17,648 --> 00:12:19,106
Why not?

153
00:12:20,818 --> 00:12:23,903
To be honest, John,
I'm all out of ideas.

154
00:12:23,947 --> 00:12:27,947
I've been cooped up in this little room all
day listening to the twisted sexual fantasies

155
00:12:27,995 --> 00:12:31,862
of a bunch of the most unattractive
housefraus you could ever wish to meet.

156
00:12:33,752 --> 00:12:39,922
Desperate for a cold beer and a nice shallow
conversation I don't have to read anything into.

157
00:12:42,304 --> 00:12:45,840
The point is, Maurice, I'm her
teacher. It's a position of trust,

158
00:12:45,892 --> 00:12:48,051
- like yours with your patients.
- Ah.

159
00:12:48,103 --> 00:12:50,393
Or should I say, most
doctors with their patients.

160
00:12:50,440 --> 00:12:54,522
That's not the point. The
point is, have you fucked her?

161
00:12:54,571 --> 00:12:59,399
The question isn't whether or not I've slept
with Anne... which, for the record, I haven't.

162
00:12:59,451 --> 00:13:01,362
- For Christ's sake.
- The question is why,

163
00:13:01,413 --> 00:13:04,533
when the idea even crossed my mind,
Istarted hearing bloody Mahler.

164
00:13:04,584 --> 00:13:07,918
- That's interesting you should choose
a Jew. - What gave you that idea?

165
00:13:07,963 --> 00:13:11,665
She's as Aryan as they come. Not that
I don't find Jewish women attractive...

166
00:13:11,718 --> 00:13:14,044
Mahler was Jewish.

167
00:13:14,096 --> 00:13:16,801
- He converted.
- Still makes him Jewish.

168
00:13:16,849 --> 00:13:20,184
- The thing is... - Please, do me
a favour, change the subject.

169
00:13:20,228 --> 00:13:22,221
Don't drag me into your neurosis.

170
00:13:22,273 --> 00:13:25,275
I get it. You're terribly
troubled, you hear music.

171
00:13:25,319 --> 00:13:29,317
Some of us out here in the real world
have plenty to worry about ourselves.

172
00:13:29,365 --> 00:13:33,447
You never seem to worry
about anything... much.

173
00:13:33,496 --> 00:13:34,825
Don't I?

174
00:13:37,960 --> 00:13:41,710
I mean, as a study in pathological
narcissism, the man's quite fascinating.

175
00:13:41,757 --> 00:13:47,049
Trouble is, instead of strapping him to the
nearest couch and frying his fucking brains out,

176
00:13:47,097 --> 00:13:49,256
everyone is taking him so literally.

177
00:13:50,643 --> 00:13:52,303
Give it time, Maurice.

178
00:13:53,313 --> 00:13:55,141
Hitler's a joke.

179
00:13:58,737 --> 00:14:00,529
He'll never last.

180
00:14:03,868 --> 00:14:07,915
Would it surprise you to learn that the
Führer himself had examined your book?

181
00:14:10,711 --> 00:14:12,835
- The Führer?
- Mm-hm.

182
00:14:15,300 --> 00:14:17,542
I'd like you to read this.

183
00:14:21,141 --> 00:14:23,549
One of our tasks here at the Chancellery

184
00:14:23,603 --> 00:14:28,516
is to process the huge volume of letters
addressed to our leader by ordinary citizens.

185
00:14:28,568 --> 00:14:30,561
They give, as you can see,

186
00:14:30,612 --> 00:14:35,525
an unrivalled insight into the spirit
of renewal alive in our country today.

187
00:14:38,622 --> 00:14:43,202
- It's very... affecting.
- Isn't it?

188
00:14:44,046 --> 00:14:48,923
The Führer has received several
such letters from the relatives of...

189
00:14:48,969 --> 00:14:52,754
unfortunates with incurable handicaps,

190
00:14:52,808 --> 00:14:56,392
requesting his special permission
to ease their suffering.

191
00:14:56,438 --> 00:14:59,558
- Hm.
- Which is where you come in.

192
00:15:01,652 --> 00:15:05,521
- Me?
- We need a paper from you, Halder,

193
00:15:05,574 --> 00:15:10,533
arguing, along the same
lines as you do in your novel,

194
00:15:10,580 --> 00:15:15,374
the case for an enlightened approach to
mercy death on the grounds of humanity.

195
00:15:17,173 --> 00:15:19,380
That's why you asked me here?

196
00:15:20,093 --> 00:15:21,338
Why else?

197
00:15:24,766 --> 00:15:27,933
I'm hardly an expert.

198
00:15:32,109 --> 00:15:35,194
My mother has been
chronically ill. Tuberculosis.

199
00:15:35,238 --> 00:15:39,402
Yes. Well, the Führer himself
said it was written from the heart.

200
00:15:39,451 --> 00:15:42,868
- Dr Goebbels was also very impressed.
- Huh.

201
00:15:42,914 --> 00:15:46,616
In fact, he thought it might make an excellent
basis for a motion picture on this theme.

202
00:15:46,669 --> 00:15:49,375
Ah.

203
00:15:49,423 --> 00:15:53,469
As for myself, I was very impressed
by the humanity of your writing.

204
00:15:54,721 --> 00:15:56,264
Thank you.

205
00:15:59,394 --> 00:16:02,978
So, that's really all
you want from me, a paper?

206
00:16:03,775 --> 00:16:06,445
You will, of course, be
very well paid for your work.

207
00:16:06,487 --> 00:16:09,441
But more than that, your
participation would be, for me,

208
00:16:09,490 --> 00:16:13,359
a guarantee that the question
of humanity remains...

209
00:16:14,288 --> 00:16:16,994
central to our whole approach.

210
00:16:17,042 --> 00:16:18,288
Uh-huh. Yes.

211
00:16:19,754 --> 00:16:23,670
I could perhaps draft
something out by next week.

212
00:16:23,718 --> 00:16:25,841
Excellent. Er, just one more thing.

213
00:16:26,888 --> 00:16:30,888
Before inviting you here we did, of
course, examine your record very thoroughly.

214
00:16:30,936 --> 00:16:36,144
Er, front-line service in 1918,
your work at the university...

215
00:16:36,192 --> 00:16:38,731
Everything... more or less in order.

216
00:16:39,905 --> 00:16:41,863
Except for one oversight.

217
00:16:43,368 --> 00:16:45,242
You never joined the Party.

218
00:16:45,913 --> 00:16:51,621
I did discuss it, on several occasions,
with my father-in -law, Dr Brunau.

219
00:16:51,671 --> 00:16:55,621
He's a prominent member
i- i-in our district.

220
00:16:55,676 --> 00:16:57,219
But at the time...

221
00:16:57,261 --> 00:17:01,592
You see... I've already
mentioned my mother's illness...

222
00:17:01,642 --> 00:17:05,640
And my life was a little...

223
00:17:07,358 --> 00:17:08,473
complicated.

224
00:17:23,838 --> 00:17:27,124
I feel such an idiot. Ineeded to
talk to you, but you'd already left,

225
00:17:27,175 --> 00:17:29,584
so I thought, "Why not come
here? You wouldn't mind. "

226
00:17:29,637 --> 00:17:33,255
- The tram took forever and I started
thinking... - Give us your wet things.

227
00:17:33,308 --> 00:17:35,882
<i>..."I can't just turn up
uninvited at this hour. "</i>

228
00:17:35,936 --> 00:17:38,226
You probably didn't even
know I had your address.

229
00:17:38,273 --> 00:17:42,651
So, I started walking up and down the road
trying to decide what to do and then...

230
00:17:42,695 --> 00:17:45,021
Well, now that you're here...

231
00:17:46,116 --> 00:17:47,694
Do sit down.

232
00:17:50,580 --> 00:17:52,822
Oh.

233
00:17:52,875 --> 00:17:54,619
Sorry.

234
00:17:54,669 --> 00:17:56,211
There you are.

235
00:17:58,132 --> 00:18:00,291
I'm sorry it's such a disaster.

236
00:18:01,511 --> 00:18:03,469
Er...

237
00:18:03,514 --> 00:18:08,261
We'd get a maid... if
we could afford one.

238
00:18:09,188 --> 00:18:11,264
I'll just dry these here.

239
00:18:13,735 --> 00:18:16,488
Maybe if that book of
mine ever gets published.

240
00:18:16,531 --> 00:18:18,274
Want something to warm you up?

241
00:18:18,325 --> 00:18:22,371
We should have a bottle of
sherry around here... somewhere.

242
00:18:23,582 --> 00:18:27,283
Unless my father-in-law's
polished it off.

243
00:18:30,508 --> 00:18:33,712
- I'm afraid we only have brandy.
- Yes, please.

244
00:18:44,234 --> 00:18:46,227
My wife's gone to bed.

245
00:18:48,990 --> 00:18:51,030
That's not to say it's late.

246
00:18:51,076 --> 00:18:54,446
She-she... She likes
to go to bed early.

247
00:18:54,497 --> 00:18:56,406
Catch up on her reading.

248
00:18:58,002 --> 00:18:59,200
- Too much?
- Uh-uh.

249
00:18:59,253 --> 00:19:00,747
Right.

250
00:19:06,470 --> 00:19:08,630
Mm. Ah!

251
00:19:12,144 --> 00:19:16,358
I've been thinking about what you said
about finding something to believe in.

252
00:19:19,070 --> 00:19:22,689
And have you... found something?

253
00:19:23,410 --> 00:19:26,079
- Yes, I think I have.
- Mm.

254
00:19:29,667 --> 00:19:31,744
It hasn't solved my problem.

255
00:19:32,505 --> 00:19:36,967
- Problem? With history?
- People. That's what I've realised.

256
00:19:37,011 --> 00:19:42,350
People are what matter. They're so
much more fascinating than ideas.

257
00:19:42,392 --> 00:19:49,643
Well... y-y-you could think of changing
course to something more vocational.

258
00:19:49,694 --> 00:19:51,485
I want to be with you.

259
00:19:52,447 --> 00:19:53,692
Hm.

260
00:19:56,995 --> 00:20:03,331
Um, I wish all my students
were so... appreciative.

261
00:20:19,733 --> 00:20:22,438
You couldn't get it up? Fuck!

262
00:20:22,486 --> 00:20:26,485
- Shh! Maurice!
- What? Not at all? Not even a twitch?

263
00:20:26,533 --> 00:20:29,072
Not... entirely.

264
00:20:32,124 --> 00:20:33,998
Maurice! Maurice!

265
00:20:35,503 --> 00:20:38,671
- Look, look, you'd had a lot
to drink, right? - Yes.

266
00:20:38,715 --> 00:20:40,792
You're under a lot of pressure.

267
00:20:43,221 --> 00:20:46,757
- I was a bit... overwhelmed.
- Well, there you go.

268
00:20:46,809 --> 00:20:50,096
It's been a long time since
I'd done anything so...

269
00:20:52,109 --> 00:20:53,436
impulsive.

270
00:20:58,324 --> 00:21:03,534
- And there was Helen...
- Ah, yes, the lovely Helen. How is she?

271
00:21:09,047 --> 00:21:12,713
I couldn't sleep. I
wanted to play something.

272
00:21:13,845 --> 00:21:16,384
- Well, I was just on my way up.
- All right.

273
00:21:23,899 --> 00:21:27,020
- It's... It's another one of my students.
- Ah.

274
00:21:27,070 --> 00:21:29,776
She... Soaking wet, poor thing.

275
00:21:30,867 --> 00:21:35,946
Can't very well go home on a night
like this. I've made up a bed.

276
00:21:37,042 --> 00:21:39,035
Oh, will he be warm enough?

277
00:21:41,631 --> 00:21:44,835
<i>"She. " I gave her a blanket, so...</i>

278
00:21:45,928 --> 00:21:49,013
Erm... Who'll make breakfast?

279
00:21:50,100 --> 00:21:51,975
I'll make her breakfast!

280
00:21:56,400 --> 00:21:58,025
Are you all right?

281
00:22:01,323 --> 00:22:06,782
- I've... I've had some brandy.
- Mm. Come here.

282
00:22:08,624 --> 00:22:10,499
What is it, John?

283
00:22:19,305 --> 00:22:20,716
Your father...

284
00:22:21,808 --> 00:22:26,388
told me I'd never get anywhere
unless I joined the Party.

285
00:22:28,484 --> 00:22:33,277
Normally, my father saying something
would make you do exactly the opposite.

286
00:22:36,828 --> 00:22:38,785
What if he's right?

287
00:22:39,581 --> 00:22:43,200
I hate to see you
agonise like this, John.

288
00:22:46,590 --> 00:22:49,129
Have a little faith in yourself.

289
00:22:51,889 --> 00:22:53,966
You'll do the right thing.

290
00:22:55,894 --> 00:22:57,603
You always do.

291
00:23:00,609 --> 00:23:02,152
Do I?

292
00:23:06,199 --> 00:23:07,480
Look...

293
00:23:08,953 --> 00:23:12,489
I can't deny it, I do find
myself attracted to you.

294
00:23:14,669 --> 00:23:19,463
But in my circumstances as a
lecturer and a married man...

295
00:23:19,509 --> 00:23:22,178
I simply can't.

296
00:23:22,220 --> 00:23:25,387
What was that?

297
00:23:25,432 --> 00:23:29,301
- Must be the start of the parade.
- Parade? What parade?

298
00:23:29,354 --> 00:23:31,680
Isn't that why we're here?

299
00:23:31,732 --> 00:23:34,403
No, this was the most
discreet spot I could think of.

300
00:23:34,445 --> 00:23:37,197
They have to go and have another
one of their bloody rallies.

301
00:23:37,239 --> 00:23:42,911
- Let's go and watch. - No, I really
can't stand that sort of thing.

302
00:23:42,955 --> 00:23:47,868
- I'd rather slip away before we
get caught up... - Oh, come on!

303
00:23:47,920 --> 00:23:49,463
What if someone sees us?

304
00:23:49,506 --> 00:23:52,377
We'll say we bumped into
each other in the crowd.

305
00:23:52,426 --> 00:23:56,471
- Why would we even be here? - To see
what all the fuss is about, of course.

306
00:23:56,514 --> 00:24:02,555
Oh, everyone looks so happy. Anything that
makes people happy can't be bad, can it?

307
00:24:02,606 --> 00:24:08,028
Well, I do find some of it rather offensive.
The ideas behind it... or lack of them.

308
00:24:08,071 --> 00:24:10,195
But feel this energy!

309
00:24:10,240 --> 00:24:14,074
All it needs is a few good people to
help channel it in the right direction.

310
00:24:14,121 --> 00:24:16,078
- Do you really believe that?
- Yes.

311
00:24:16,123 --> 00:24:19,575
Burning all those books
- of course it's shocking, but then,

312
00:24:19,628 --> 00:24:25,335
you said so yourself, wouldn't it be liberating to
just chuck them all out and make a fresh start?

313
00:24:25,385 --> 00:24:27,960
Come on!

314
00:24:28,014 --> 00:24:32,143
There's a considerable difference between
talking about something and actually doing it.

315
00:24:32,186 --> 00:24:35,603
Exactly, men like you shouldn't be
shut up in their studies reading books.

316
00:24:35,648 --> 00:24:40,989
They should be out there, helping to
build a better country for our children.

317
00:24:41,031 --> 00:24:44,401
Come on, please. Please?

318
00:24:44,452 --> 00:24:46,112
All right, just for a bit.

319
00:24:48,457 --> 00:24:50,699
I did give serious thought
to joining the Party,

320
00:24:50,752 --> 00:24:57,255
but somehow I just couldn't quite see
myself marching around and waving banners.

321
00:25:03,727 --> 00:25:05,934
<i>What I mean is...</i>

322
00:25:05,980 --> 00:25:07,641
I...

323
00:25:07,691 --> 00:25:10,098
Perhaps you're right.

324
00:25:10,152 --> 00:25:13,604
A man of your talents would
be wasted in the rank and file.

325
00:25:14,617 --> 00:25:16,906
Sturmbannführer Dorbisch?

326
00:25:16,953 --> 00:25:21,415
Bouhler here. There's
someone I'd like you to meet.

327
00:25:22,168 --> 00:25:25,335
It's not every day we get a call
from the Chancellery of the Führer.

328
00:25:25,380 --> 00:25:29,249
I don't work there, you understand?
I'm really just an academic.

329
00:25:29,302 --> 00:25:33,633
Just an academic? Don't be ridiculous.
You served with the 24th Brandenburg!

330
00:25:33,683 --> 00:25:38,845
Inever saw much action, I'm afraid.
I was only called up in 1918.

331
00:25:38,897 --> 00:25:41,520
Ah, just in time for the last big push.

332
00:25:41,568 --> 00:25:43,277
Great times.

333
00:25:43,321 --> 00:25:47,735
- I hope you're hungry?
- No... Yes, yes.

334
00:25:47,785 --> 00:25:51,617
Well, the Kaiser, as you know, had
his elite regiment, the Imperial Guard.

335
00:25:51,664 --> 00:25:54,238
Well, now we have the Schutzsfaffel.

336
00:25:54,293 --> 00:25:56,915
Hm. The Führer's bodyguard?

337
00:25:56,963 --> 00:25:59,633
It's rather more than that.

338
00:25:59,674 --> 00:26:03,721
I'm not suggesting you have to ride
around on a running board with a revolver.

339
00:26:03,764 --> 00:26:06,090
No. No.

340
00:26:06,142 --> 00:26:11,019
We're interested in recruiting
the better type of person.

341
00:26:11,065 --> 00:26:15,230
The specialists in their
field, such as yourself.

342
00:26:15,279 --> 00:26:19,609
Well, I wouldn't exactly
call myself a specialist.

343
00:26:19,659 --> 00:26:23,575
See, that's what I like about you, Halder
- no showing off, no bragging,

344
00:26:23,623 --> 00:26:26,078
just a quiet determination.

345
00:26:26,125 --> 00:26:28,203
That's exactly the
type we're looking for.

346
00:26:28,254 --> 00:26:33,842
I... I am flattered by your high
opinion of me, but my worry is that...

347
00:26:34,762 --> 00:26:38,298
with my work at the university, I
might not be able to contribute...

348
00:26:38,350 --> 00:26:42,978
The last thing we want is for you to
be distracted from your valuable work,

349
00:26:43,023 --> 00:26:45,349
shaping the minds of
our next generation.

350
00:26:45,401 --> 00:26:48,818
No, your position would
be an honorary one.

351
00:26:49,865 --> 00:26:53,615
The greatest minds in the
land with us in spirit.

352
00:26:57,083 --> 00:27:01,581
Helen, something rather
extraordinary has happened.

353
00:27:02,716 --> 00:27:06,050
It's all because of the
book, would you believe?

354
00:27:07,221 --> 00:27:11,006
They really seem to love
it, for some unknown reason.

355
00:27:13,479 --> 00:27:17,478
Helen... I'm trying
to tell you something.

356
00:27:18,277 --> 00:27:20,484
Sorry? What did you say?

357
00:27:21,198 --> 00:27:22,608
John!

358
00:27:23,617 --> 00:27:25,575
Is that you, John?

359
00:27:27,163 --> 00:27:28,492
Yes!

360
00:27:58,162 --> 00:27:59,787
Come back to bed.

361
00:28:38,131 --> 00:28:39,507
Maurice?

362
00:28:41,427 --> 00:28:46,221
There you are. I was beginning to think
she was playing a practical joke on me.

363
00:28:46,267 --> 00:28:49,138
- Who?
- Helen. Sending me here.

364
00:28:49,979 --> 00:28:54,525
- What's this all about?
- I needed somewhere I could work in peace.

365
00:28:54,568 --> 00:28:57,357
- Who is it?
- Shh!

366
00:28:57,406 --> 00:29:01,322
Sorry, I'm a bit distracted.

367
00:29:02,496 --> 00:29:06,329
Right, come on! You've got time
for a quick drink. I've had a...

368
00:29:06,376 --> 00:29:09,580
- I've had a lot of cancellations. Come on.
- I'm afraid I really can't.

369
00:29:09,630 --> 00:29:12,751
- Just one. There's always time for one.
- I can't, Maurice.

370
00:29:12,801 --> 00:29:14,878
- You're not coming down?
- No.

371
00:29:16,639 --> 00:29:19,261
- All right, let me in for a minute.
- No! I mean...

372
00:29:19,310 --> 00:29:22,146
I'm... I'm working.

373
00:29:22,188 --> 00:29:23,564
Jesus!

374
00:29:26,528 --> 00:29:29,778
- You all right?
- Why shouldn't I be?

375
00:29:29,823 --> 00:29:36,409
Well, you're here and Helen's... more
than usually abstract, shall we say?

376
00:29:37,541 --> 00:29:39,084
My couch is free.

377
00:29:41,088 --> 00:29:43,377
You know I can't afford you.

378
00:29:44,551 --> 00:29:46,924
But you can afford the
rent on a bachelor flat?

379
00:29:46,971 --> 00:29:50,221
Well, that depends if I ever get
to finish this paper I'm writing.

380
00:29:51,685 --> 00:29:53,762
All right.

381
00:29:53,813 --> 00:29:55,770
I know where I'm not wanted.

382
00:29:57,526 --> 00:29:58,902
Maurice...

383
00:30:01,198 --> 00:30:05,066
We'll get together when things have
calmed down a little. I promise.

384
00:30:06,037 --> 00:30:07,615
Don't do me any favours.

385
00:30:10,042 --> 00:30:11,834
I'd like you to meet Anne.

386
00:30:12,587 --> 00:30:14,461
Delighted, Frau Professor, delighted.

387
00:30:14,506 --> 00:30:19,253
- Oh no, we're not... Anne and I...
- What a wonderful place for a party.

388
00:30:19,304 --> 00:30:21,297
- Freddie.
- Cheers.

389
00:30:21,348 --> 00:30:25,561
John here is working on a secret assignment
for the Chancellery of the Führer.

390
00:30:25,604 --> 00:30:30,019
It's a... brief paper that...
that had to be drafted.

391
00:30:30,069 --> 00:30:32,026
I teach at the university.

392
00:30:32,071 --> 00:30:34,148
Then you must know Theodore.

393
00:30:35,242 --> 00:30:36,357
Of course.

394
00:30:37,536 --> 00:30:43,244
Once it would have given me great satisfaction
to see you at a gathering such as this.

395
00:30:43,294 --> 00:30:50,462
But accepting your duties as a National Socialist
is no excuse for shirking them as a husband!

396
00:30:50,512 --> 00:30:55,389
I worry for the movement when it
embraces men of such moral weakness.

397
00:30:55,434 --> 00:30:59,219
Ishould explain. Doctor
Brunau is my father-in -law.

398
00:30:59,273 --> 00:31:02,725
- My wife and I are separated. - To think
you abandoned Helen for this whore.

399
00:31:02,777 --> 00:31:07,488
There's no need to bring Anne
into it. The fault is mine.

400
00:31:08,410 --> 00:31:10,984
If you'll excuse us. Anne?

401
00:31:14,960 --> 00:31:17,878
Why should we leave? You're
not the one who's drunk.

402
00:31:17,922 --> 00:31:21,090
- Bastard!
- Where do you think you're going?

403
00:31:21,134 --> 00:31:24,670
Elisabeth, darling, would you mind
taking care of Anne for a few moments?

404
00:31:24,723 --> 00:31:26,467
Ineed to have a quiet word with John.

405
00:31:26,516 --> 00:31:29,055
- You don't have any children, do you?
- Not yet.

406
00:31:29,103 --> 00:31:30,848
No, you're much too young.

407
00:31:30,898 --> 00:31:32,974
If I have to listen to
one more proud mother

408
00:31:33,025 --> 00:31:36,395
gushing about the orienteering
prize the little horse won at camp...

409
00:31:36,446 --> 00:31:39,947
- I'm sorry... - I don't know
about you, I could do with a drink.

410
00:31:39,993 --> 00:31:45,285
No need to apologise. If you're in with
us, John, the old rules no longer apply.

411
00:31:47,210 --> 00:31:48,621
Himmler...

412
00:31:50,507 --> 00:31:53,923
He might look like a bank manager, but
you've got to give the man one thing -

413
00:31:53,969 --> 00:31:56,757
very advanced views on sex.

414
00:31:56,806 --> 00:32:00,472
He wants us to go out, he wants us to
knock up girls left, right and centre

415
00:32:00,519 --> 00:32:04,269
so that they can... donate
a child to the Führer.

416
00:32:05,150 --> 00:32:08,603
- Well, it's our patriotic duty,
for God's sake. -

417
00:32:08,655 --> 00:32:14,327
So long as it's the right sort of girl, that is.
Not that you've got any problems on that score.

418
00:32:15,330 --> 00:32:17,573
She looks like a bloody Rhinemaiden.

419
00:32:18,835 --> 00:32:20,709
She does, doesn't she?

420
00:32:21,505 --> 00:32:25,634
Really, mother!

421
00:32:25,677 --> 00:32:30,886
- I'm unpacking. No... - It's not time
to unpack. We haven't left yet.

422
00:32:30,933 --> 00:32:33,141
But I've only just arrived.

423
00:32:33,187 --> 00:32:37,649
No, Mother. You woke up
here this morning, remember?

424
00:32:37,693 --> 00:32:42,190
You've been here a long time
and now you're going home.

425
00:32:42,240 --> 00:32:43,699
The house is on fire.

426
00:32:43,742 --> 00:32:45,949
The house isn't...

427
00:32:47,706 --> 00:32:49,117
Oh, my God!

428
00:32:50,460 --> 00:32:51,870
Carry on.

429
00:32:54,924 --> 00:32:58,175
- What are you doing?
- I was going to fry the onions.

430
00:32:59,762 --> 00:33:01,305
Do you have to do it this minute?

431
00:33:01,348 --> 00:33:04,718
I want to do it while you're
here so you can put me right!

432
00:33:05,812 --> 00:33:11,057
There was a time when I wouldn't have felt it so
much, you saying that you loved somebody else!

433
00:33:11,111 --> 00:33:14,730
But a few weeks ago Istarted falling
in love with you all over again.

434
00:33:14,782 --> 00:33:19,576
- It was as if you'd-you'd suddenly
come alive! - Yes, that's how it felt.

435
00:33:22,292 --> 00:33:24,332
Ispoke to Father.

436
00:33:24,378 --> 00:33:28,425
- Did he make an awful scene?
- I had it coming.

437
00:33:28,467 --> 00:33:31,718
Oh! I can't bear the idea
of him thinking badly of you.

438
00:33:31,763 --> 00:33:33,341
He has every reason to.

439
00:33:33,390 --> 00:33:36,594
But he doesn't know what I'm like,
what you've had to put up with!

440
00:33:36,644 --> 00:33:38,886
Helen! Don't...

441
00:33:38,938 --> 00:33:41,063
Please, don't be nice to me.

442
00:33:41,109 --> 00:33:43,398
I'm not being nice to you.

443
00:33:50,620 --> 00:33:52,744
Mother, what happened?

444
00:33:53,792 --> 00:33:55,868
I was trying to come downstairs.

445
00:33:55,920 --> 00:33:57,165
Ow!

446
00:33:57,213 --> 00:34:00,583
- Are you all right?
- Yes.

447
00:34:02,135 --> 00:34:04,627
- What have you
done? - Oh-oh!

448
00:34:11,982 --> 00:34:16,147
- Couldn't you have waited for me?
- I can't wait around all day.

449
00:34:16,196 --> 00:34:18,604
The piano is driving me mad!

450
00:34:20,660 --> 00:34:23,864
- Wait, Mother, wait!
- Come on, come on.

451
00:34:24,665 --> 00:34:27,203
Come on. Come on.

452
00:34:27,251 --> 00:34:29,957
- Are you sure you are all right?
- Yes, I'm all right.

453
00:34:30,005 --> 00:34:32,212
You scared me.

454
00:34:32,258 --> 00:34:34,631
- We're on our way.
- At last!

455
00:34:35,596 --> 00:34:37,340
You're really leaving?

456
00:34:38,266 --> 00:34:40,058
Helen, please...

457
00:34:40,101 --> 00:34:42,890
Chat, chat, chat. Don't
know what you've got to talk about.

458
00:34:42,939 --> 00:34:45,098
- You told me you were finished with her.
- Stop it.

459
00:34:45,150 --> 00:34:50,775
Look, if I asked you one more time,
please stay, would it make any difference?

460
00:34:52,118 --> 00:34:55,238
I'll come back tomorrow. We'll
talk about it then, I promise.

461
00:34:55,288 --> 00:34:57,577
If we don't get Mother to
the car now, we never will.

462
00:34:57,624 --> 00:35:01,410
- He won't come back.
- Please, stay out of it!

463
00:35:01,463 --> 00:35:03,337
If you'd have been a proper wife to him

464
00:35:03,382 --> 00:35:05,458
- this wouldn't have happened.
- How dare you?

465
00:35:05,510 --> 00:35:08,180
She's a wonderful wife in
ways you'll never understand!

466
00:35:08,222 --> 00:35:10,298
So, why are you leaving?

467
00:35:11,726 --> 00:35:13,719
Ineed to go to the toilet.

468
00:35:13,771 --> 00:35:15,728
Bloody hell!

469
00:35:18,903 --> 00:35:20,563
Good idea, Mother.

470
00:35:23,241 --> 00:35:25,115
Before we get going.

471
00:35:27,204 --> 00:35:29,696
What is this place?

472
00:35:29,750 --> 00:35:31,873
You said you were thirsty.

473
00:35:31,919 --> 00:35:35,123
A glass of water to take my pills.

474
00:35:35,173 --> 00:35:37,297
I'm sure they serve water.

475
00:35:38,594 --> 00:35:40,053
There we are.

